Here's the deal. I need to post more. I need to document more. I need to be more visible. I need to be more vulnerable. I need to get words out of my head.

Welcome to the start of something new for me. I have a lot to talk about. Some of it might even be interesting or funny.

I have a post from a while ago explaining what I wanted to do. I failed to follow that idea. However, now I have some things to talk about. I'm pretty jazzed about the things I've been doing, both at work and at home. I've taken up some really interesting projects in both realms. Here's a breif overview to get things up to speed:

## Work projects

We've been busy with creating many new looks at data and cultivating a much more open discussion about various metrics. I plan to dedicate some more words towards these projects in times to come, so I won't elaborate much more currently.

Our district webpage was updated to a new design. However, the tech department wasn't consulted with the testing or implementing of the changes, so lots of things broke. The individual who headed the project put minimal effort towards it seemingly, because they quit shortly after it was launched. On issue was they renamed the page that parents went to, which broke nearly everything that we share out to parents, which is who we share the most out to. So it was a big scrabble to set up redirects, find broken links, and fix a laundry list of issues I found within just an hour of sitting down after launch. More issues came out of the closet as time went on, it was not fun. I didn't mind giving up the reins to someone else, and thankfully now we have someone who can understand how things work a bit better in that position now.

I've recently made some major improvements to some course recommendation stuff that I will share with you all shortly. Really dug into some Google Apps Script stuff to automate a majority of the steps I would do by hand.

Stay tuned.

## Personal Projects

I've been working on a few projects for the last 6 months or so that have really excited me.

First, I've got the self-hosting bug. With a lot of my thoughts going towards reducing my dependency towards larger corporations, I've really wanted to get into ways I could develop or find ways to be more self-dependent in my tech use. I will dive much deeper into the specifics, but I can start here. I had a 2016 Razer Blade that I replaced with my current Macbook (which is really amazing, coming from a noted Apple hater) just laying around. So I decided to try and make it into a server platform of some sort. After spending a lot of time with Gemini and Claude, I learned quite a bit about the process and what it takes to have everything going. With an addition of 24TBs in storage space, I have quite a few things going, all of which seem very stable (knock on wood). I will cover much of what I'm hosting and doing in future posts.

To piggyback off of this, I've started to self-host my music. I've been wanting to get more intentional in my music listening. Also, getting higher quality music files has made me really appreciate music a bit more. The downside of only have access to music you have on-hand, you have a hard time finding new music that you don't know about. There can be some ways to find new music by artist you already like, but finding actually new artist and albums can be difficult. So, I've started building a music recommendation system that can help look at my library and recommend music I haven't rated or listened to previously, all base don things I've liked previously. I can also be a vibe listener, so I have started putting together a way to have album picks based on the vibe I'm feeling.

The last big thing is what I'm calling The Docket. I've been on the lookout for a simple way to easily make notes and tasks work together, and by extension, turning plans into action. I know what you are thinking, "Oh, great another note-taking app." The thing is, I've used a large amount of them. None have fit the bill for me. My brain works through scratch, though fragments. You can give me all the templates or complex setups in the world, but all I need is something to take notes and make tasks. I've started laying down the framework and getting many of the actions working so far. It's really exciting to me.

## The future

So there is the basics. I still want to explore fiction writing and other commentary, but tech has really got a hold of me.

Until the next, cheers.
